": "61430"}, {"t": "Monterey Mist", "w": "61429"}, {"t": "True Blues", "w": "123712"}, {"t": "Blues In C Minor", "w": "41695"}, {"t": "Blues In H (b)", "w": "5906"}, {"t": "Namesake", "w": "59599"}, {"t": "Really True Blues", "w": "61427"}], "quotes": [], "about_quotes": [{"speaker": "James Moody", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "Ray Brown [phonetic sp.], bass, Milton Jackson [phonetic sp.], vibraharp [phonetic sp.]. Know, Howard Johnson [phonetic sp.], lead alto, you know. Cecil Payne [phonetic sp.], Ernie Henry [phonetic sp.]. Yeah. So. And I'm -- I was 21 years old.", "doc_title": "James Moody — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Moody-James/Moody_James_Transcript.pdf"}, {"speaker": "James Moody", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "When I joined Dizzy’s band in ‘46 it was I think, Monk was the piano player, Thelonious Monk, and Kenny Clarke was the drummer, Ray Brown bass, Milton Jackson vibraharp", "doc_title": "James Moody interviewed by Monk Rowe, San Diego, California, February 13, 1998", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/james-moody-interviewed-monk-rowe-san-diego-california-february-13-1998"}, {"speaker": "Mary Lou Williams", "relation": "played with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "Bags - you know, with the Modern - came in and I said, 'I have to go up to the ladies' rest-room. Will you sit and play a set for me?' He said, 'Yes, Lou.' So he sat down and while I was up there I was using toilet paper to write down the notes the way he was pushing.", "doc_title": "53571_Mary Lou Williams oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/53571/"}, {"speaker": "Kenny Burrell", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "So in that band was John Coltrane and Percy Heath... myself and Dizzy... Milt maybe once in awhile... So that’s when I first got to know Coltrane. I knew Bags, Milt Jackson, before that and I got to know Percy Heath. So then we made my first records then.", "doc_title": "Kenny Burrell — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Burrell-Kenny/Burrell_Kenny_Transcript.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Ray Brown", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "he picked up another guy two weeks later, Milt Jackson... All you want to do is get on the bandstand and play that music. Because if you’ve got enough money to eat — at times Jackson and I only had money just for dinner.", "doc_title": "Ray Brown interviewed by Monk Rowe, Scottsdale, AZ, April 16, 2000", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/ray-brown-interviewed-monk-rowe-scottsdale-az-april-16-2000"}, {"speaker": "Jimmy Cobb", "relation": "played with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "So our band had – our rhythm section had to play with them... We’d come on, and Miles would play Move. Bird would play one of his blues. Milt Jackson would play The Devil and the Deep Blue Sea... That’s how we all met.", "doc_title": "Jimmy Cobb — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://americanhistory.si.edu/sites/default/files/file-uploader/Jimmy-Cobb-Transcription-2020.pdf"}]}